00:02:16.550 --> 00:02:18.260
that I struggled in.

00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:20.270
And when I sat down
to write it there,

00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:23.210
I was about 500 or
thousand words deep,

00:02:23.210 --> 00:02:25.966
and it was all disclaimers of
like, "well just so you know,

00:02:25.966 --> 00:02:27.590
I'm actually pretty
good at this stuff.

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:29.230
So it's not that I'm bad at it."

00:02:29.230 --> 00:02:31.670
And the idea of actually
looking directly

00:02:31.670 --> 00:02:33.140
at where I had
struggled and where

00:02:33.140 --> 00:02:36.710
I had failed in this class, it
was like looking at the sun.

00:02:36.710 --> 00:02:41.187
It was really hard to just
bring my focus towards that.

00:02:41.187 --> 00:02:42.770
And in some sense,
most of the writing

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:45.260
I've done since then
flows out of that,

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:49.730
I think trying to look at the
experience, which is really not

00:02:49.730 --> 00:02:52.610
fun to look at, but of
being in a math class,

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:54.740
running into something
that you don't understand,

00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:56.600
and just kind of
feeling like an idiot.

00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:59.420
Which is something, if you take
enough math, you wind up there.

00:02:59.420 --> 00:03:00.961
I mean, everybody
has that experience

00:03:00.961 --> 00:03:02.107
at one point or another.

00:03:02.107 --> 00:03:04.190
Anyway, and so that was,
from the start, something

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:08.290
that I was thinking
about with the blog.

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:11.100
Another piece, this was a year
or two later, a similar angle.

00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:14.870
And you can see my
drawing style evolving.

00:03:14.870 --> 00:03:18.650
Basically, not
trying to do as much.

00:03:18.650 --> 00:03:20.270
No noses, no hands.

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:23.390
This was in the midst of what
I call my Long Neck Phase,

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:26.240
where all my stick figures had
necks that were much too long.

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:28.010
And also, I think,
understanding what,

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:30.950
as someone who has no
background in drawing

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:34.520
and really no comfort
with it as a medium

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:37.580
or as a skill, what
can I do is basically

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:39.890
try to come up with
some concepts for images

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:44.730
and have the concept override
my lack of technique.

00:03:44.730 --> 00:03:48.680
So this was one where I
think a common kind of meme

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:50.120
in the culture
around mathematics

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:52.700
is that you hit
some maximum point.

00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:54.574
For some people, it's algebra 1.

00:03:54.574 --> 00:03:56.990
For some people, it's their
trigonometry or calculus class

00:03:56.990 --> 00:03:57.770
in high school.

00:03:57.770 --> 00:03:59.900
For some people, they
take abstract algebra,

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:01.280
and they start learning
about rings and fields,

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:03.321
and that's where they sort
of fall off the wagon.

00:04:03.321 --> 00:04:05.446
And there's this
notion that yeah,

00:04:05.446 --> 00:04:07.070
there's a ceiling
that you can advance.

00:04:07.070 --> 00:04:08.270
Math is hierarchical.

00:04:08.270 --> 00:04:09.350
You climb the ladder.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:10.740
Then you get to a rung,
and it's like, oh,

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:12.656
you can't go past that
one, because your lungs

00:04:12.656 --> 00:04:14.040
don't work that high.

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:16.524
Which I think is wrong.

00:04:16.524 --> 00:04:17.940
I don't think
that's how it works,

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:21.890
but it's a very authentic
experience that people have.

00:04:21.890 --> 00:04:25.250
So I show this as just
as an example of the kind

00:04:25.250 --> 00:04:28.250
of the kind of cartooning I do.

00:04:28.250 --> 00:04:31.580
My metaphor is this futon.

00:04:31.580 --> 00:04:33.150
It was freshman year of college.

00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:35.390
And you may remember
this, actually.

00:04:35.390 --> 00:04:37.119
The guys on the
first floor in our--

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:38.660
yeah, we had the
same entryway, yeah.

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:40.070
The guys on the
first floor wanted

00:04:40.070 --> 00:04:41.000
to get rid of their futon.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:42.050
So they're very
nicely carried it up

00:04:42.050 --> 00:04:43.460
to the fourth floor for us.

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:46.651
And along the way, like
a little piece broke off.

00:04:46.651 --> 00:04:48.650
And we were like, ah,
it's a little piece of it.

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:50.150
It was like a little
piece of metal.

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:50.930
It seemed fine.

00:04:50.930 --> 00:04:54.690
And then, like a week later,
the futon was doing that.

00:04:54.690 --> 00:04:57.240
And then two weeks later,
it was sort of like that,

00:04:57.240 --> 00:04:58.190
dumping in the middle.

00:04:58.190 --> 00:05:00.140
And then eventually, it
took like a month or two,

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:01.390
and then the futon was broken.

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:04.700
And I think that to me isn't
a bad metaphor for what

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:07.550
happens in math
education, where there's

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:09.080
a little piece that's missing.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:13.010
I've taught eighth grade, so
an algebra 1 student can graph

00:05:13.010 --> 00:05:17.330
some lines, maybe doesn't
really get what that's about,

00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:19.550
doesn't get the idea of
sort of the correspondence

00:05:19.550 --> 00:05:23.270
between this equation and the
points on the line or xy pairs

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:25.564
that satisfy the equation.

00:05:25.564 --> 00:05:27.230
There's just some
missing understanding,

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:28.740
and it seems fine
in eighth grade,

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:30.300
because they can answer
all the questions.

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:32.180
But as you build further,
the futon kind of

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:35.679
starts to warp, and then at
some point, there's a collapse.

00:05:35.679 --> 00:05:37.220
I think that's what
people experience

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:39.712
as a ceiling in math education.

00:05:39.712 --> 00:05:42.170
It's not actually them hitting
some kind of cognitive limit

00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:43.340
of what they can understand.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:48.050
It's sort of old fractures
finally leading to a rupture.

